# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: github-actions
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:github-actions/github] It is commonly used to host open source software development projects.
[src:github-actions/github] As of January 2023, GitHub reported having over 100 million developers and more than 420 million repositories, including at least 28 million public repositories.
[src:github-actions/github] It is the world's largest source code host as of June 2023.
[src:github-actions/github] Over five billion developer contributions were made to more than 500 million open source projects in 2024.
[src:github-actions/github] The development of the GitHub platform began on October 19, 2007.
[src:github-actions/github] The site was launched in April 2008 by Tom Preston-Werner, Chris Wanstrath, P.
[src:github-actions/github] Hyett, and Scott Chacon after it had been available for a few months as a beta release.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub was originally a flat organization with no middle managers, instead relying on self-management.
[src:github-actions/github] Employees could choose to work on projects that interested them (open allocation), but the chief executive set salaries.
[src:github-actions/github] In 2014, the company added a layer of middle management in response to harassment allegations against its co-founder and then-CEO, Thomas Preston-Werner, and his wife Theresa.
[src:github-actions/github] As a result of the scandal, Preston-Werner resigned from his position as CEO.
[src:github-actions/github] Co-founder and product lead, Chris Wanstrath, became CEO.
[src:github-actions/github] Julio Avalos, then general counsel and administrative officer, assumed control over GitHub's business operations and day-to-day management.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub was a bootstrapped start-up business, which in its first years provided enough revenue to be funded solely by its three founders and start taking on employees.
[src:github-actions/github] In July 2012, four years after the company was founded, Andreessen Horowitz invested $100 million in venture capital with a $750 million valuation.
[src:github-actions/github] In July 2015 GitHub raised another $250 million (~$322 million in 2024) of venture capital in a series B round.
[src:github-actions/github] The lead investor was Sequoia Capital, and other investors were Andreessen Horowitz, Thrive Capital, IVP (Institutional Venture Partners), and other venture capital funds.
[src:github-actions/github] The company was then valued at approximately $2 billion.
[src:github-actions/github] As of 2023, GitHub was estimated to generate $1 billion in revenue annually.
[src:github-actions/github] The GitHub service was developed by Chris Wanstrath, P.
[src:github-actions/github] Hyett, Tom Preston-Werner, and Scott Chacon using Ruby on Rails, and started in February 2008.
[src:github-actions/github] The company, GitHub, Inc., was formed in 2007 and is located in San Francisco.
[src:github-actions/github] On February 24, 2009, GitHub announced that within the first year of being online, GitHub had accumulated over 46,000 public repositories, 17,000 of which were formed in the previous month.
[src:github-actions/github] At that time, about 6,200 repositories had been forked at least once, and 4,600 had been merged.
[src:github-actions/github] That same year, the site was used by over 100,000 users, according to GitHub, and had grown to host 90,000 unique public repositories, 12,000 having been forked at least once, for a total of 135,000 repositories.
[src:github-actions/github] In 2010, GitHub was hosting 1 million repositories.
[src:github-actions/github] ReadWriteWeb reported that GitHub had surpassed SourceForge and Google Code in total number of commits for the period of January to May 2011.
[src:github-actions/github] On January 16, 2013, GitHub passed the 3 million users mark and was then hosting more than 5 million repositories.
[src:github-actions/github] By the end of the year, the number of repositories was twice as great, reaching 10 million repositories.
[src:github-actions/github] In 2015, GitHub opened an office in Japan, its first outside of the U.S.
[src:github-actions/github] On February 28, 2018, GitHub fell victim to the third-largest distributed denial-of-service (DDoS) attack in history, with incoming traffic reaching a peak of about 1.35 terabits per second.
[src:github-actions/github] On June 19, 2018, GitHub expanded its GitHub Education by offering free education bundles to all schools.
[src:github-actions/github] On June 11, 2019, it was announced that former Bitnami chief operating officer (COO) and co-founder, Erica Brescia, would be GitHub's COO.
[src:github-actions/github] On November 3, 2021, GitHub announced that CEO Nat Friedman, who became CEO when Microsoft acquired GitHub, was stepping down as CEO and GitHub's chief product officer, Thomas Dohmke, would become CEO on November 15.
[src:github-actions/github] In June 2025, the amount of repositories on GitHub surpassed one billion.
[src:github-actions/github] Notably, the billionth repository contained nothing but the word "shit".
[src:github-actions/github] On August 11, 2025 Thomas Dohmke announced that he was to step down as CEO at the end of 2025, to pursue entrepreneurial endeavors; Microsoft did not immediately share its intention to find a direct replacement.
[src:github-actions/github] On June 4, 2018, Microsoft announced its intent to acquire GitHub for US$7.5 billion (~$9.2 billion in 2024).
[src:github-actions/github] According to Microsoft, GitHub continued to operate independently as a community, platform and business.
[src:github-actions/github] Under Microsoft, the service was led by Xamarin's Nat Friedman, reporting to Scott Guthrie, executive vice president of Microsoft Cloud and AI.
[src:github-actions/github] There have been concerns from developers Kyle Simpson, JavaScript trainer and author, and Rafael Laguna, CEO at Open-Xchange over Microsoft's purchase, citing uneasiness over Microsoft's handling of previous acquisitions, such as Nokia's mobile business and Skype.
[src:github-actions/github] This acquisition was in line with Microsoft's business strategy under CEO Satya Nadella, which has seen a larger focus on cloud computing services, alongside the development of and contributions to open-source software.
[src:github-actions/github] *Harvard Business Review* argued that Microsoft was intending to acquire GitHub to get access to its user base, so it can be used as a loss leader to encourage the use of its other development products and services.
[src:github-actions/github] Concerns over the sale bolstered interest in competitors: Bitbucket (owned by Atlassian), SourceForge (owned by Slashdot) and GitLab reported that they had seen spikes in new users intending to migrate projects from GitHub to their respective services.
[src:github-actions/github] In September 2019, GitHub acquired Semmle, a code analysis tool.
[src:github-actions/github] In February 2020, GitHub launched in India under the name GitHub India Private Limited.
[src:github-actions/github] In March 2020, GitHub announced that it was acquiring npm, a JavaScript packaging vendor, for an undisclosed sum of money.
[src:github-actions/github] In early July 2020, the GitHub Archive Program was established to archive its open-source code in perpetuity.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub's mascot is Mona, an anthropomorphized "octocat" with five octopus-like arms.
[src:github-actions/github] The character was created by graphic designer Simon Oxley as clip art to sell on iStock, a website that enables designers to market royalty-free digital images.
[src:github-actions/github] The illustration GitHub chose was a character that Oxley had named Octopuss.
[src:github-actions/github] Since GitHub wanted Octopuss for their logo (a use that the iStock license disallows), they negotiated with Oxley to buy exclusive rights to the image.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub renamed Octopuss to Octocat, and trademarked the character along with the new name.
[src:github-actions/github] Later, GitHub hired illustrator Cameron McEfee to adapt Octocat for different purposes on the website and promotional materials; McEfee and various GitHub users have since created hundreds of variations of the character, which are available on The Octodex.
[src:github-actions/github] Projects on GitHub can be accessed and managed using the standard Git command-line interface; all standard Git commands work with it.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub also allows users to browse public repositories on the site.
[src:github-actions/github] Multiple desktop clients and Git plugins are also available.
[src:github-actions/github] In addition, the site provides social networking-like functions such as feeds, followers, wikis (using wiki software called Gollum), and a social network graph to display how developers work on their versions ("forks") of a repository and what fork (and branch within that fork) is newest.
[src:github-actions/github] Anyone can browse and download public repositories, but only registered users can contribute content to repositories.
[src:github-actions/github] With a registered user account, users can have discussions, manage repositories, submit contributions to others' repositories, and review changes to code.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub began offering limited private repositories at no cost in January 2019 (limited to three contributors per project).
[src:github-actions/github] Previously, only public repositories were free.
[src:github-actions/github] On April 14, 2020, GitHub made "all of the core GitHub features" free for everyone, including "private repositories with unlimited collaborators." In May 2019 Github, Inc. began encrypting source code on github.com by default.
[src:github-actions/github] The fundamental software that underpins GitHub is Git, written by Linus Torvalds, creator of Linux.
[src:github-actions/github] The additional software that provides the GitHub user interface was written using Ruby on Rails and Erlang by GitHub, Inc. developers Wanstrath, Hyett, and Preston-Werner.
[src:github-actions/github] The primary purpose of GitHub is to facilitate the version control and issue tracking aspects of software development.
[src:github-actions/github] Labels, milestones, responsibility assignment, and a search engine are available for issue tracking.
[src:github-actions/github] For version control, Git (and, by extension, GitHub) allows pull requests to propose changes to the source code.
[src:github-actions/github] Users who can review the proposed changes can see a diff between the requested changes and approve them.
[src:github-actions/github] In Git terminology, this action is called "committing" and one instance of it is a "commit." A history of all commits is kept and can be viewed at a later time.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub's Terms of Service do not require public software projects hosted on GitHub to meet the Open Source Definition.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub Enterprise is a self-managed version of GitHub with similar functionality.
[src:github-actions/github] It can be run on an organization's hardware or a cloud provider and has been available as of November 2011.
[src:github-actions/github] In November 2020, source code for GitHub Enterprise Server was leaked online in an apparent protest against DMCA takedown of youtube-dl.
[src:github-actions/github] According to GitHub, the source code came from GitHub accidentally sharing the code with Enterprise customers themselves, not from an attack on GitHub servers.
[src:github-actions/github] In 2008, GitHub introduced GitHub Pages, a static web hosting service for blogs, project documentation, and books.
[src:github-actions/github] All GitHub Pages content is stored in a Git repository as files served to visitors verbatim or in Markdown format.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub is integrated with the Jekyll static website and blog generator and GitHub continuous integration pipelines.
[src:github-actions/github] Each time the content source is updated, Jekyll regenerates the website and automatically serves it via GitHub Pages infrastructure.
[src:github-actions/github] Like the rest of GitHub, it includes free and paid service tiers.
[src:github-actions/github] Websites generated through this service are hosted either as subdomains of the github.io domain or can be connected to custom domains bought through a third-party domain name registrar.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub Actions was officially launched on November 13, 2019.
[src:github-actions/github] It was first announced in October 2018 at GitHub Universe as a way to automate workflows, but the full general availability (GA) release came a year later in 2019.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub Actions, which allows building continuous integration and continuous deployment pipelines for testing, releasing and deploying software without the use of third-party websites/platforms.
[src:github-actions/github] Unlike many other CI/CD tools, GitHub Actions launched with a marketplace where developers could share and reuse prebuilt actions (e.g., testing, linting, deployments).
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub wanted to reduce reliance on third-party services and keep developers within the GitHub ecosystem.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub Actions provided hosted runners (Linux, Windows, macOS) that could dynamically scale, eliminating the need for self-managed build servers.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub also operates a pastebin-style site called **Gist**, which is for code snippets, as opposed to GitHub proper, which is usually used for larger projects.
[src:github-actions/github] Tom Preston-Werner débuted the feature at a Ruby conference in 2008.
[src:github-actions/github] Gist builds on the traditional simple concept of a pastebin by adding version control for code snippets, easy forking, and TLS encryption for private pastes.
[src:github-actions/github] Because each "gist" is its own Git repository, multiple code snippets can be contained in a single page, and they can be pushed and pulled using Git.
[src:github-actions/github] Unregistered users could upload Gists until March 19, 2018, when uploading Gists was restricted to logged-in users, reportedly to mitigate spamming on the page of recent Gists.
[src:github-actions/github] Gists' URLs use hexadecimal IDs, and edits to Gists are recorded in a revision history, which can show the text difference of thirty revisions per page with an option between a "split" and "unified" view.
[src:github-actions/github] Like repositories, Gists can be forked, "starred", i.e., publicly bookmarked, and commented on.
[src:github-actions/github] The count of revisions, stars, and forks is indicated on the gist page.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub launched a new program called the GitHub Student Developer Pack to give students free access to more than a dozen popular development tools and services.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub partnered with Bitnami, Crowdflower, DigitalOcean, DNSimple, HackHands, Namecheap, Orchestrate, Screen hero, SendGrid, Stripe, Travis CI, and Unreal Engine to launch the program.
[src:github-actions/github] In 2016, GitHub announced the launch of the GitHub Campus Experts program to train and encourage students to grow technology communities at their universities.
[src:github-actions/github] The Campus Experts program is open to university students 18 years and older worldwide.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub Campus Experts are one of the primary ways that GitHub funds student-oriented events and communities, Campus Experts are given access to training, funding, and additional resources to run events and grow their communities.
[src:github-actions/github] To become a Campus Expert, applicants must complete an online training course with multiple modules to develop community leadership skills.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub also provides some software as a service (SaaS) integrations for adding extra features to projects.
[src:github-actions/github] In 2019, GitHub officially launched its native mobile applications for both iOS and Android.
[src:github-actions/github] This announcement was made during GitHub Universe 2019, with the apps being released in beta for iOS initially, followed by an Android beta and full public release in early 2020.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub Sponsors allows users to make monthly money donations to projects hosted on GitHub.
[src:github-actions/github] The public beta was announced on May 23, 2019, and the project accepts waitlist registrations.
[src:github-actions/github] Furthermore, users can still use similar services like Patreon and Open Collective and link to their websites.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub Copilot was one of the first widely adopted AI-assisted software development tools.
[src:github-actions/github] The preview launched in 2021 for VSCode users and was based on OpenAI's Codex model.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub Copilot is now available to use on GitHub.com directly, on the command line, as well as in several IDEs.
[src:github-actions/github] Users are able to choose from a range of LLMs for some features.
[src:github-actions/github] User requests to block the Copilot features have been the #1 and #2 most popular topics of the past 12 months on GitHub's organization community page as of September 2025.
[src:github-actions/github] Some users and projects have moved to open source alternatives such as Codeberg.
[src:github-actions/github] In July 2020, GitHub stored a February archive of the site in an abandoned mountain mine in Svalbard, Norway, part of the Arctic World Archive and not far from the Svalbard Global Seed Vault.
[src:github-actions/github] The archive contained the code of all active public repositories, as well as that of dormant but significant public repositories.
[src:github-actions/github] The 21TB of data was stored on *piqlFilm* archival film reels as matrix (2D) barcode (Boxing barcode), and is expected to last 500–1,000 years.
[src:github-actions/github] The GitHub Archive Program is also working with partners on Project Silica, in an attempt to store all public repositories for 10,000 years.
[src:github-actions/github] It aims to write archives into the molecular structure of quartz glass platters, using a high-precision petahertz pulse laser, i.e. one that pulses a quadrillion (1,000,000,000,000,000) times per second.
[src:github-actions/github] In March 2014, GitHub programmer Julie Ann Horvath alleged that founder and CEO Tom Preston-Werner engaged in a pattern of harassment against her that led to her leaving the company.
[src:github-actions/github] In April 2014, GitHub released a statement denying Horvath's allegations.
[src:github-actions/github] However, following an internal investigation, GitHub confirmed the claims.
[src:github-actions/github] On July 25, 2019, a developer based in Iran wrote on Medium that GitHub had blocked his private repositories and prohibited access to GitHub pages.
[src:github-actions/github] Soon after, GitHub confirmed that it was now blocking developers in Iran, Crimea, Cuba, North Korea, and Syria from accessing private repositories.
[src:github-actions/github] However, GitHub reopened access to GitHub Pages days later, for public repositories regardless of location.
[src:github-actions/github] It was also revealed that using GitHub while visiting sanctioned countries could result in similar actions occurring on a user's account.
[src:github-actions/github] Developers who feel that they should not have restrictions can appeal for the removal of said restrictions, including those who only travel to, and do not reside in, those countries.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub has forbidden the use of VPNs and IP proxies to access the site from sanctioned countries, as purchase history and IP addresses are how it flags users, among other sources.
[src:github-actions/github] On December 4, 2014, Russia blacklisted GitHub.com because GitHub initially refused to take down user-posted suicide manuals.
[src:github-actions/github] After a day, Russia withdrew its block, and GitHub began blocking specific content and pages in Russia.
[src:github-actions/github] On December 31, 2014, India blocked GitHub.com along with 31 other websites over pro-ISIS content posted by users; the block was lifted three days later.
[src:github-actions/github] On October 8, 2016, Turkey blocked GitHub to prevent email leakage of a hacked account belonging to the country's energy minister.
[src:github-actions/github] On March 26, 2015, a large-scale DDoS attack was launched against GitHub.com that lasted for just under five days.
[src:github-actions/github] The attack, which appeared to originate from China, primarily targeted GitHub-hosted user content describing methods of circumventing Internet censorship.
[src:github-actions/github] GitHub has a $200,000 contract with U.S.
[src:github-actions/github] Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE) for the use of their on-site product GitHub Enterprise Server.
[src:github-actions/github] This contract was renewed in 2019, despite internal opposition from many GitHub employees.
[src:github-actions/github] As of November 13, 2019, five workers had resigned over the contract.
[src:github-actions/github] The ICE contract dispute came into focus again in June 2020 due to the company's decision to abandon "master/slave" branch terminology, spurred by the George Floyd protests and Black Lives Matter movement.
[src:github-actions/github] Detractors of GitHub describe the branch renaming to be a form of performative activism and have urged GitHub to cancel its ICE contract instead.
[src:github-actions/github] An open letter from members of the open source community was shared on GitHub in December 2019, demanding that the company drop its contract with ICE and provide more transparency into how it conducts business and partnerships.
[src:github-actions/github] The letter has been signed by more than 700 people.
[src:github-actions/github] In January 2021, GitHub fired one of its employees after he expressed concern for colleagues following the January 6 United States Capitol attack, calling some of the rioters "Nazis".
[src:github-actions/github] After an investigation, GitHub's COO said there were "significant errors of judgment and procedure" with the company's decision to fire the employee.
[src:github-actions/github] As a result of the investigation, GitHub reached out to the employee, and the company's head of human resources resigned.
[src:github-actions/github] In 2023, parts of the social media platform Twitter were uploaded onto GitHub.
[src:github-actions/github] The leak was first reported by the *New York Times* and was part of a legal filing Twitter submitted to the United States District Court for the Northern District of California.
[src:github-actions/github] Twitter claimed that the postings infringed on copyright property owned by them, and asked the court for information to identify the user who posted the source code to GitHub, under the username "FreeSpeechEnthusiast".
[src:github-actions/github] In 2012, Linus Torvalds, the original developer of Git, highly praised GitHub, stating, "The hosting of github [*sic*] is excellent.
[src:github-actions/github] As a result, I consider GitHub useless for these kinds of things.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] Learn the basics of core concepts and essential terminology in GitHub Actions.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] GitHub Actions is a continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD) platform that allows you to automate your build, test, and deployment pipeline.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] You can create workflows that build and test every pull request to your repository, or deploy merged pull requests to production.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] GitHub Actions goes beyond just DevOps and lets you run workflows when other events happen in your repository.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] For example, you can run a workflow to automatically add the appropriate labels whenever someone creates a new issue in your repository.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] GitHub provides Linux, Windows, and macOS virtual machines to run your workflows, or you can host your own self-hosted runners in your own data center or cloud infrastructure.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] You can configure a GitHub Actions **workflow** to be triggered when an **event** occurs in your repository, such as a pull request being opened or an issue being created.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] Your workflow contains one or more **jobs** which can run in sequential order or in parallel.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] Each job will run inside its own virtual machine **runner**, or inside a container, and has one or more **steps** that either run a script that you define or run an **action**, which is a reusable extension that can simplify your workflow.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] (Diagram of an event triggering Runner 1 to run Job 1, which triggers Runner 2 to run Job 2.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] A **workflow** is a configurable automated process that will run one or more jobs.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] Workflows are defined by a YAML file checked in to your repository and will run when triggered by an event in your repository, or they can be triggered manually, or at a defined schedule.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] Workflows are defined in the `.github/workflows` directory in a repository.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] You can reference a workflow within another workflow.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] For more information, see Reuse workflows.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] For more information, see Writing workflows.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] An **event** is a specific activity in a repository that triggers a **workflow** run.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] For example, an activity can originate from GitHub when someone creates a pull request, opens an issue, or pushes a commit to a repository.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] You can also trigger a workflow to run on a schedule, by posting to a REST API, or manually.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] For a complete list of events that can be used to trigger workflows, see Events that trigger workflows.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] A **job** is a set of **steps** in a workflow that is executed on the same **runner**.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] Each step is either a shell script that will be executed, or an **action** that will be run.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] Steps are executed in order and are dependent on each other.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] Since each step is executed on the same runner, you can share data from one step to another.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] For example, you can have a step that builds your application followed by a step that tests the application that was built.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] Steps run in order by default, but you can also run selected steps concurrently when your workflow benefits from parallel execution, such as starting a long-running service while later steps continue.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] For more information, see Workflow syntax for GitHub Actions.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] You can configure a job's dependencies with other jobs; by default, jobs have no dependencies and run in parallel.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] When a job takes a dependency on another job, it waits for the dependent job to complete before running.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] You can also use a **matrix** to run the same job multiple times, each with a different combination of variables—like operating systems or language versions.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] For example, you might configure multiple build jobs for different architectures without any job dependencies and a packaging job that depends on those builds.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] The build jobs run in parallel, and once they complete successfully, the packaging job runs.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] For more information, see Choosing what your workflow does.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] An **action** is a pre-defined, reusable set of jobs or code that performs specific tasks within a **workflow**, reducing the amount of repetitive code you write in your workflow files.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] You can write your own actions, or you can find actions to use in your workflows in the GitHub Marketplace.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] For more information on actions, see Reusing automations.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] A **runner** is a server that runs your workflows when they're triggered.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] Each runner can run a single **job** at a time.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] GitHub provides Ubuntu Linux, Microsoft Windows, and macOS runners to run your **workflows**.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] Each workflow run executes in a fresh, newly-provisioned virtual machine.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] GitHub also offers larger runners, which are available in larger configurations.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] For more information, see Using larger runners.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] If you need a different operating system or require a specific hardware configuration, you can host your own runners.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] For more information about self-hosted runners, see Managing self-hosted runners.
[src:github-actions/understanding-github-actions] GitHub Actions can help you automate nearly every aspect of your application development processes.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] A workflow is a configurable automated process made up of one or more jobs.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You must create a YAML file to define your workflow configuration.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Workflow files use YAML syntax, and must have either a `.yml` or `.yaml` file extension.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you're new to YAML and want to learn more, see Learn YAML in Y minutes.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You must store workflow files in the `.github/workflows` directory of your repository.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] GitHub displays the names of your workflows under your repository's "Actions" tab.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you omit `name`, GitHub displays the workflow file path relative to the root of the repository.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The name for workflow runs generated from the workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] GitHub displays the workflow run name in the list of workflow runs on your repository's "Actions" tab.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If `run-name` is omitted or is only whitespace, then the run name is set to event-specific information for the workflow run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For example, for a workflow triggered by a `push` or `pull_request` event, it is set as the commit message or the title of the pull request.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] This value can include expressions and can reference the `github` and `inputs` contexts.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] To automatically trigger a workflow, use `on` to define which events can cause the workflow to run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For a list of available events, see Events that trigger workflows.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can define single or multiple events that can trigger a workflow, or set a time schedule.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can also restrict the execution of a workflow to only occur for specific files, tags, or branch changes.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] These options are described in the following sections.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can specify a single event or multiple events.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you specify multiple events, only one of those events needs to occur to trigger your workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If multiple triggering events for your workflow occur at the same time, multiple workflow runs will be triggered.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Some events have activity types that give you more control over when your workflow should run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Use `on.<event_name>.types` to define the type of event activity that will trigger a workflow run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For example, the `issue_comment` event has the `created`, `edited`, and `deleted` activity types.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If your workflow triggers on the `label` event, it will run whenever a label is created, edited, or deleted.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you specify the `created` activity type for the `label` event, your workflow will run when a label is created but not when a label is edited or deleted.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you specify multiple activity types, only one of those event activity types needs to occur to trigger your workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If multiple triggering event activity types for your workflow occur at the same time, multiple workflow runs will be triggered.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For example, the following workflow triggers when an issue is opened or labeled.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If an issue with two labels is opened, three workflow runs will start: one for the issue opened event and two for the two issue labeled events.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information about each event and their activity types, see Events that trigger workflows.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Some events have filters that give you more control over when your workflow should run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For example, the `push` event has a `branches` filter that causes your workflow to run only when a push to a branch that matches the `branches` filter occurs, instead of when any push occurs.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you specify activity types or filters for an event and your workflow triggers on multiple events, you must configure each event separately.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You must append a colon (`:`) to all events, including events without configuration.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Use `on.<event_name>.types` to define the type of activity that will trigger a workflow run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Most GitHub events are triggered by more than one type of activity.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For example, the `label` is triggered when a label is `created`, `edited`, or `deleted`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The `types` keyword enables you to narrow down activity that causes the workflow to run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When only one activity type triggers a webhook event, the `types` keyword is unnecessary.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When using the `pull_request` and `pull_request_target` events, you can configure a workflow to run only for pull requests that target specific branches.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Use the `branches` filter when you want to include branch name patterns or when you want to both include and exclude branch names patterns.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Use the `branches-ignore` filter when you only want to exclude branch name patterns.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You cannot use both the `branches` and `branches-ignore` filters for the same event in a workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you define both `branches`/`branches-ignore` and `paths`/`paths-ignore`, the workflow will only run when both filters are satisfied.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The `branches` and `branches-ignore` keywords accept glob patterns that use characters like `*`, `**`, `+`, `?`, `!` and others to match more than one branch name.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If a name contains any of these characters and you want a literal match, you need to escape each of these special characters with `\`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information about glob patterns, see the Workflow syntax for GitHub Actions.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The patterns defined in `branches` are evaluated against the Git ref's name.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If a workflow is skipped due to branch filtering, path filtering, or a commit message, then checks associated with that workflow will remain in a "Pending" state.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] A pull request that requires those checks to be successful will be blocked from merging.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When a pattern matches the `branches-ignore` pattern, the workflow will not run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The patterns defined in `branches-ignore` are evaluated against the Git ref's name.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You cannot use `branches` and `branches-ignore` to filter the same event in a single workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you want to both include and exclude branch patterns for a single event, use the `branches` filter along with the `!` character to indicate which branches should be excluded.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you define a branch with the `!` character, you must also define at least one branch without the `!` character.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you only want to exclude branches, use `branches-ignore` instead.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The order that you define patterns matters.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The following workflow will run on `pull_request` events for pull requests that target `releases/10` or `releases/beta/mona`, but not for pull requests that target `releases/10-alpha` or `releases/beta/3-alpha` because the negative pattern `!releases/**-alpha` follows the positive pattern.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When using the `push` event, you can configure a workflow to run on specific branches or tags.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Use the `tags` filter when you want to include tag name patterns or when you want to both include and exclude tag names patterns.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Use the `tags-ignore` filter when you only want to exclude tag name patterns.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You cannot use both the `tags` and `tags-ignore` filters for the same event in a workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you define only `tags`/`tags-ignore` or only `branches`/`branches-ignore`, the workflow won't run for events affecting the undefined Git ref.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you define neither `tags`/`tags-ignore` or `branches`/`branches-ignore`, the workflow will run for events affecting either branches or tags.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The `branches`, `branches-ignore`, `tags`, and `tags-ignore` keywords accept glob patterns that use characters like `*`, `**`, `+`, `?`, `!` and others to match more than one branch or tag name.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If a name contains any of these characters and you want a literal match, you need to *escape* each of these special characters with `\`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The patterns defined in `branches` and `tags` are evaluated against the Git ref's name.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When a pattern matches the `branches-ignore` or `tags-ignore` pattern, the workflow will not run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can't use `branches` and `branches-ignore` to filter the same event in a single workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Similarly, you can't use `tags` and `tags-ignore` to filter the same event in a single workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you want to both include and exclude branch or tag patterns for a single event, use the `branches` or `tags` filter along with the `!` character to indicate which branches or tags should be excluded.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Similarly, if you define a tag with the `!` character, you must also define at least one tag without the `!` character.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you only want to exclude tags, use `tags-ignore` instead.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The following workflow will run on pushes to `releases/10` or `releases/beta/mona`, but not on `releases/10-alpha` or `releases/beta/3-alpha` because the negative pattern `!releases/**-alpha` follows the positive pattern.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When using the `push` and `pull_request` events, you can configure a workflow to run based on what file paths are changed.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Path filters are not evaluated for pushes of tags.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Use the `paths` filter when you want to include file path patterns or when you want to both include and exclude file path patterns.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Use the `paths-ignore` filter when you only want to exclude file path patterns.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You cannot use both the `paths` and `paths-ignore` filters for the same event in a workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you want to both include and exclude path patterns for a single event, use the `paths` filter prefixed with the `!` character to indicate which paths should be excluded.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The `paths` and `paths-ignore` keywords accept glob patterns that use the `*` and `**` wildcard characters to match more than one path name.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information, see the Workflow syntax for GitHub Actions.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If at least one path matches a pattern in the `paths` filter, the workflow runs.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For example, the following workflow would run anytime you push a JavaScript file (`.js`).
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If a workflow is skipped due to path filtering, branch filtering, or a commit message, then checks associated with that workflow will remain in a "Pending" state.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When all the path names match patterns in `paths-ignore`, the workflow will not run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If any path names do not match patterns in `paths-ignore`, even if some path names match the patterns, the workflow will run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] A workflow with the following path filter will only run on `push` events that include at least one file outside the `docs` directory at the root of the repository.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You cannot use `paths` and `paths-ignore` to filter the same event in a single workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you define a path with the `!` character, you must also define at least one path without the `!` character.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you only want to exclude paths, use `paths-ignore` instead.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] This example runs anytime the `push` event includes a file in the `sub-project` directory or its subdirectories, unless the file is in the `sub-project/docs` directory.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For example, a push that changed `sub-project/index.js` or `sub-project/src/index.js` will trigger a workflow run, but a push changing only `sub-project/docs/readme.md` will not.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you push more than 1,000 commits, or if GitHub does not generate the diff due to a timeout, the workflow will always run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The filter determines if a workflow should run by evaluating the changed files and running them against the `paths-ignore` or `paths` list.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If there are no files changed, the workflow will not run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If there are files changed that aren't matched in the first 300 files returned by the filter, the workflow will not run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You may need to create more specific filters so that the workflow will run automatically.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information, see About comparing branches in pull requests.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can use `on.schedule` to define a time schedule for your workflows.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Use POSIX cron syntax to schedule workflows to run at specific times.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] By default, scheduled workflows run in UTC.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can optionally specify a timezone using an IANA timezone string for timezone-aware scheduling.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Scheduled workflows run on the latest commit on the default branch.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The shortest interval you can run scheduled workflows is once every 5 minutes.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For schedules that set `timezone` to a time zone that observes daylight saving time (DST), during DST spring-forward transitions, scheduled workflows in skipped hours advance to the next valid time.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For example, a 2:30 AM schedule advances to 3:00 AM.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Cron syntax has five fields separated by a space, and each field represents a unit of time.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] A single workflow can be triggered by multiple `schedule` events.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Access the `schedule` event that triggered the workflow through the `github.event.schedule` context.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] This example triggers the workflow to run at 5:30 UTC every Monday-Thursday, and 17:30 UTC on Tuesdays and Thursdays, but skips the `Not on Monday or Wednesday` step on Monday and Wednesday.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information about `schedule` events, see Events that trigger workflows.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Use `on.workflow_call` to define the inputs and outputs for a reusable workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can also map the secrets that are available to the called workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information on reusable workflows, see Reuse workflows.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When using the `workflow_call` keyword, you can optionally specify inputs that are passed to the called workflow from the caller workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information about the `workflow_call` keyword, see Events that trigger workflows.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] In addition to the standard input parameters that are available, `on.workflow_call.inputs` requires a `type` parameter.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information, see `on.workflow_call.inputs.<input_id>.type`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If a `default` parameter is not set, the default value of the input is `false` for a boolean, `0` for a number, and `""` for a string.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Within the called workflow, you can use the `inputs` context to refer to an input.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information, see Contexts reference.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If a caller workflow passes an input that is not specified in the called workflow, this results in an error.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Required if input is defined for the `on.workflow_call` keyword.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The value of this parameter is a string specifying the data type of the input.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] This must be one of: `boolean`, `number`, or `string`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Called workflow outputs are available to all downstream jobs in the caller workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Each output has an identifier, an optional `description,` and a `value.` The `value` must be set to the value of an output from a job within the called workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] In the example below, two outputs are defined for this reusable workflow: `workflow_output1` and `workflow_output2`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] These are mapped to outputs called `job_output1` and `job_output2`, both from a job called `my_job`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For information on how to reference a job output, see `jobs.<job_id>.outputs`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] A map of the secrets that can be used in the called workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Within the called workflow, you can use the `secrets` context to refer to a secret.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you are passing the secret to a nested reusable workflow, then you must use `jobs.<job_id>.secrets` again to pass the secret.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If a caller workflow passes a secret that is not specified in the called workflow, this results in an error.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] A string identifier to associate with the secret.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] A boolean specifying whether the secret must be supplied.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When using the `workflow_run` event, you can specify what branches the triggering workflow must run on in order to trigger your workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The `branches` and `branches-ignore` filters accept glob patterns that use characters like `*`, `**`, `+`, `?`, `!` and others to match more than one branch name.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For example, a workflow with the following trigger will run when the workflow named `Build` runs on a branch that is named `releases/10` or `releases/beta/mona` but will not `releases/10-alpha`, `releases/beta/3-alpha`, or `main`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When using the `workflow_dispatch` event, you can optionally specify inputs that are passed to the workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] This trigger only receives events when the workflow file is on the default branch.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The triggered workflow receives the inputs in the `inputs` context.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] A boolean specifying whether the input must be supplied.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] This must be one of: `boolean`, `choice`, `number`, `environment` or `string`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can use `permissions` to modify the default permissions granted to the `GITHUB_TOKEN`, adding or removing access as required, so that you only allow the minimum required access.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information, see Use GITHUB_TOKEN for authentication in workflows.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can use `permissions` either as a top-level key, to apply to all jobs in the workflow, or within specific jobs.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When you add the `permissions` key within a specific job, all actions and run commands within that job that use the `GITHUB_TOKEN` gain the access rights you specify.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information, see `jobs.<job_id>.permissions`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Owners of an organization can restrict write access for the `GITHUB_TOKEN` at the repository level.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information, see Disabling or limiting GitHub Actions for your organization.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When a workflow is triggered by the `pull_request_target` event, the `GITHUB_TOKEN` is granted read/write repository permission, even when it is triggered from a public fork.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information, see Events that trigger workflows.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For each of the available permissions, shown in the table below, you can assign one of the access levels: `read` (if applicable), `write`, or `none`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If you specify the access for any of these permissions, all of those that are not specified are set to `none`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can define the access that the `GITHUB_TOKEN` will permit by specifying `read`, `write`, or `none` as the value of the available permissions within the `permissions` key.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can use the `permissions` key to add and remove read permissions for forked repositories, but typically you can't grant write access.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The exception to this behavior is where an admin user has selected the **Send write tokens to workflows from pull requests** option in the GitHub Actions settings.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information, see Managing GitHub Actions settings for a repository.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The permissions for the `GITHUB_TOKEN` are initially set to the default setting for the enterprise, organization, or repository.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] If the default is set to the restricted permissions at any of these levels then this will apply to the relevant repositories.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For example, if you choose the restricted default at the organization level then all repositories in that organization will use the restricted permissions as the default.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] The permissions are then adjusted based on any configuration within the workflow file, first at the workflow level and then at the job level.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Finally, if the workflow was triggered by a pull request event other than `pull_request_target` from a forked repository, and the **Send write tokens to workflows from pull requests** setting is not selected, the permissions are adjusted to change any write permissions to read only.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can specify `permissions` at the top level of a workflow, so that the setting applies to all jobs in the workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] This example shows permissions being set for the `GITHUB_TOKEN` that will apply to all jobs in the workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] All permissions are granted read access.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can use the `permissions` key to add and remove `read` permissions for forked repositories, but typically you can't grant `write` access.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Workflow runs triggered by Dependabot pull requests run as if they are from a forked repository, and therefore use a read-only `GITHUB_TOKEN`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] These workflow runs cannot access any secrets.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For information about strategies to keep these workflows secure, see Secure use reference.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] A `map` of variables that are available to the steps of all jobs in the workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can also set variables that are only available to the steps of a single job or to a single step.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information, see `jobs.<job_id>.env` and `jobs.<job_id>.steps[*].env`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Variables in the `env` map cannot be defined in terms of other variables in the map.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When more than one environment variable is defined with the same name, GitHub uses the most specific variable.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For example, an environment variable defined in a step will override job and workflow environment variables with the same name, while the step executes.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] An environment variable defined for a job will override a workflow variable with the same name, while the job executes.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Use `defaults` to create a `map` of default settings that will apply to all jobs in the workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can also set default settings that are only available to a job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information, see `jobs.<job_id>.defaults`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] When more than one default setting is defined with the same name, GitHub uses the most specific default setting.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For example, a default setting defined in a job will override a default setting that has the same name defined in a workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can use `defaults.run` to provide default `shell` and `working-directory` options for all `run` steps in a workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You can also set default settings for `run` that are only available to a job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] For more information, see `jobs.<job_id>.defaults.run`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] You cannot use contexts or expressions in this keyword.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Use `shell` to define the `shell` for a step.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] This keyword can reference several contexts.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Use `working-directory` to define the working directory for the `shell` for a step.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p01] Ensure the `working-directory` you assign exists on the runner before you run your shell in it.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Use `concurrency` to ensure that only a single job or workflow using the same concurrency group will run at a time.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] A concurrency group can be any string or expression.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The expression can only use `github`, `inputs` and `vars` contexts.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information about expressions, see Evaluate expressions in workflows and actions.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can also specify `concurrency` at the job level.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information, see `jobs.<job_id>.concurrency`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] This means that there can be at most one running job or workflow in a concurrency group at any time.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] When a concurrent job or workflow is queued, if another job or workflow using the same concurrency group in the repository is in progress, the queued job or workflow will be `pending`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] By default, any existing `pending` job or workflow in the same concurrency group will be canceled and the new queued job or workflow will take its place.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] To also cancel any currently running job or workflow in the same concurrency group, specify `cancel-in-progress: true`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] To conditionally cancel currently running jobs or workflows in the same concurrency group, you can specify `cancel-in-progress` as an expression with any of the allowed expression contexts.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] To allow more than one `pending` job or workflow run to wait in the same concurrency group, use the optional `queue` property.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The combination of `queue: max` and `cancel-in-progress: true` is not allowed and will result in a workflow validation error.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The default behavior of GitHub Actions is to allow multiple jobs or workflow runs to run concurrently.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The `concurrency` keyword allows you to control the concurrency of workflow runs.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Concurrency groups provide a way to manage and limit the execution of workflow runs or jobs that share the same concurrency key.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The `concurrency` key is used to group workflows or jobs together into a concurrency group.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] When you define a `concurrency` key, GitHub Actions ensures that only one workflow or job with that key runs at any given time.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] If a new workflow run or job starts with the same `concurrency` key, GitHub Actions will cancel any workflow or job already running with that key.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The `concurrency` key can be a hard-coded string, or it can be a dynamic expression that includes context variables.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] It is possible to define concurrency conditions in your workflow so that the workflow or job is part of a concurrency group.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] This means that when a workflow run or job starts, GitHub will cancel any workflow runs or jobs that are already in progress in the same concurrency group.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] This is useful in scenarios where you want to prevent parallel runs for a certain set of a workflows or jobs, such as the ones used for deployments to a staging environment, in order to prevent actions that could cause conflicts or consume more resources than necessary.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] In this example, `job-1` is part of a concurrency group named `staging_environment`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] This means that if a new run of `job-1` is triggered, any runs of the same job in the `staging_environment` concurrency group that are already in progress will be cancelled.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Alternatively, using a dynamic expression such as `concurrency: ci-${{ github.ref }}` in your workflow means that the workflow or job would be part of a concurrency group named `ci-` followed by the reference of the branch or tag that triggered the workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] By default, only one job or workflow run can be `pending` in a concurrency group at a time.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] To allow multiple runs to queue instead of being canceled, set `queue: max`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] With `queue: max`, up to 100 jobs or workflow runs can wait in the concurrency group; once the queue is full, any additional runs are canceled.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Note that `queue: max` cannot be combined with `cancel-in-progress: true`, because the two options describe conflicting behaviors for handling in-progress runs.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Note that in this example, without defining a particular concurrency group, GitHub Actions will cancel *any* in-progress run of the job or workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] If you build the group name with a property that is only defined for specific events, you can use a fallback value.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For example, `github.head_ref` is only defined on `pull_request` events.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] If your workflow responds to other events in addition to `pull_request` events, you will need to provide a fallback to avoid a syntax error.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The following concurrency group cancels in-progress jobs or runs on `pull_request` events only; if `github.head_ref` is undefined, the concurrency group will fallback to the run ID, which is guaranteed to be both unique and defined for the run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] If you have multiple workflows in the same repository, concurrency group names must be unique across workflows to avoid canceling in-progress jobs or runs from other workflows.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Otherwise, any previously in-progress or pending job will be canceled, regardless of the workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] If you would like to cancel in-progress jobs on certain branches but not on others, you can use conditional expressions with `cancel-in-progress`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For example, you can do this if you would like to cancel in-progress jobs on development branches but not on release branches.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] In this example, multiple pushes to a `release/1.2.3` branch would not cancel in-progress runs.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Pushes to another branch, such as `main`, would cancel in-progress runs.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] A workflow run is made up of one or more `jobs`, which run in parallel by default.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] To run jobs sequentially, you can define dependencies on other jobs using the `jobs.<job_id>.needs` keyword.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Each job runs in a runner environment specified by `runs-on`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can run an unlimited number of jobs as long as you are within the workflow usage limits.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information, see Billing and usage for GitHub-hosted runners and Actions limits for self-hosted runner usage limits.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] If you need to find the unique identifier of a job running in a workflow run, you can use the GitHub API.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information, see REST API endpoints for GitHub Actions.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Use `jobs.<job_id>` to give your job a unique identifier.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The key `job_id` is a string and its value is a map of the job's configuration data.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You must replace `<job_id>` with a string that is unique to the `jobs` object.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The `<job_id>` must start with a letter or `_` and contain only alphanumeric characters, `-`, or `_`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] In this example, two jobs have been created, and their `job_id` values are `my_first_job` and `my_second_job`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Use `jobs.<job_id>.name` to set a name for the job, which is displayed in the GitHub UI.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For a specific job, you can use `jobs.<job_id>.permissions` to modify the default permissions granted to the `GITHUB_TOKEN`, adding or removing access as required, so that you only allow the minimum required access.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] By specifying the permission within a job definition, you can configure a different set of permissions for the `GITHUB_TOKEN` for each job, if required.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Alternatively, you can specify the permissions for all jobs in the workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For information on defining permissions at the workflow level, see `permissions`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] This example shows permissions being set for the `GITHUB_TOKEN` that will only apply to the job named `stale`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Write access is granted for the `issues` and `pull-requests` permissions.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] All other permissions will have no access.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Use `jobs.<job_id>.needs` to identify any jobs that must complete successfully before this job will run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] If a job fails or is skipped, all jobs that need it are skipped unless the jobs use a conditional expression that causes the job to continue.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] If a run contains a series of jobs that need each other, a failure or skip applies to all jobs in the dependency chain from the point of failure or skip onwards.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] If you would like a job to run even if a job it is dependent on did not succeed, use the `always()` conditional expression in `jobs.<job_id>.if`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] In this example, `job1` must complete successfully before `job2` begins, and `job3` waits for both `job1` and `job2` to complete.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] In this example, `job3` uses the `always()` conditional expression so that it always runs after `job1` and `job2` have completed, regardless of whether they were successful.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information, see Evaluate expressions in workflows and actions.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can use the `jobs.<job_id>.if` conditional to prevent a job from running unless a condition is met.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can use any supported context and expression to create a conditional.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information on which contexts are supported in this key, see Contexts reference.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The `jobs.<job_id>.if` condition is evaluated before `jobs.<job_id>.strategy.matrix` is applied.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] When you use expressions in an `if` conditional, you can, optionally, omit the `${{ }}` expression syntax because GitHub Actions automatically evaluates the `if` conditional as an expression.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] However, this exception does not apply everywhere.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You must always use the `${{ }}` expression syntax or escape with `''`, `""`, or `()` when the expression starts with `!`, since `!` is reserved notation in YAML format.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] This example uses `if` to control when the `production-deploy` job can run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] It will only run if the repository is named `octo-repo-prod` and is within the `octo-org` organization.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Otherwise, the job will be marked as *skipped*.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Use `jobs.<job_id>.runs-on` to define the type of machine to run the job on.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Quotation marks are not required around simple strings like `self-hosted`, but they are required for expressions like `"${{ inputs.chosen-os }}"`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] If you use a GitHub-hosted runner, each job runs in a fresh instance of a runner image specified by `runs-on`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The value for runs-on, when you are using a GitHub-hosted runner, is a workflow label or the name of a runner group.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The labels for the standard GitHub-hosted runners are shown in the following tables.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information, see GitHub-hosted runners.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For public repositories, jobs using the workflow labels shown in the table below will run with the associated specifications.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] With the exception of single-CPU runners, each GitHub-hosted runner is a new virtual machine (VM) hosted by GitHub.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Single-CPU runners are hosted in a container on a shared VM—see GitHub-hosted runners reference.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Use of the standard GitHub-hosted runners is free and unlimited on public repositories.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For private repositories, jobs using the workflow labels shown in the table below will run on virtual machines with the associated specifications.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] These runners use your GitHub account's allotment of free minutes, and are then charged at the per minute rates.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] In addition to the standard GitHub-hosted runners, GitHub offers customers on GitHub Team and GitHub Enterprise Cloud plans a range of managed virtual machines with advanced features - for example, more cores and disk space, GPU-powered machines, and ARM-powered machines.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information, see Larger runners.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The `-latest` runner images are the latest stable images that GitHub provides, and might not be the most recent version of the operating system available from the operating system vendor.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Beta and Deprecated Images are provided "as-is", "with all faults" and "as available" and are excluded from the service level agreement and warranty.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Beta Images may not be covered by customer support.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] To specify a self-hosted runner for your job, configure `runs-on` in your workflow file with self-hosted runner labels.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Self-hosted runners may have the `self-hosted` label.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] When setting up a self-hosted runner, by default we will include the label `self-hosted`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You may pass in the `--no-default-labels` flag to prevent the self-hosted label from being applied.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Labels can be used to create targeting options for runners, such as operating system or architecture, we recommend providing an array of labels that begins with `self-hosted` (this must be listed first) and then includes additional labels as needed.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] When you specify an array of labels, jobs will be queued on runners that have all the labels that you specify.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Actions Runner Controller does not support the `self-hosted` label.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information, see Self-hosted runners and Using self-hosted runners in a workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can use `runs-on` to target runner groups, so that the job will execute on any runner that is a member of that group.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more granular control, you can also combine runner groups with labels.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Runner groups can only have larger runners or self-hosted runners as members.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] In this example, runners have been added to a group called `build-runners`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] When you combine groups and labels, the runner must meet both requirements to be eligible to run the job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can use `jobs.<job_id>.snapshot` to generate a custom image.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Add the snapshot keyword to the job, using either the string syntax or mapping syntax as shown in Generating a custom image.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Each job that includes the snapshot keyword creates a separate image.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] To generate only one image or image version, include all workflow steps in a single job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Each successful run of a job that includes the snapshot keyword creates a new version of that image.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information, see Using custom images.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Use `jobs.<job_id>.environment` to define the environment that the job references.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can provide the environment as only the environment `name`, or as an environment object with the `name` and `url`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The URL maps to `environment_url` in the deployments API.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information about the deployments API, see REST API endpoints for repositories.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] All deployment protection rules must pass before a job referencing the environment is sent to a runner.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information, see Managing environments for deployment.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The value of `url` can be an expression.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Allowed expression contexts: `github`, `inputs`, `vars`, `needs`, `strategy`, `matrix`, `job`, `runner`, `env`, and `steps`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The value of `name` can be an expression.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Allowed expression contexts: `github`, `inputs`, `vars`, `needs`, `strategy`, and `matrix`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Set `deployment` to `false` to use an environment's secrets and variables without creating a deployment object.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Setting `deployment: false` is not compatible with custom deployment protection rules.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information, see Deploying with GitHub Actions.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can use `jobs.<job_id>.concurrency` to ensure that only a single job or workflow using the same concurrency group will run at a time.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can also specify `concurrency` at the workflow level.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information, see `concurrency`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can use `jobs.<job_id>.outputs` to create a `map` of outputs for a job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Job outputs are available to all downstream jobs that depend on this job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information on defining job dependencies, see `jobs.<job_id>.needs`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Outputs can be a maximum of 1 MB per job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] The total of all outputs in a workflow run can be a maximum of 50 MB.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Size is approximated based on UTF-16 encoding.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Job outputs containing expressions are evaluated on the runner at the end of each job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Outputs containing secrets are redacted on the runner and not sent to GitHub Actions.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] If an output is skipped because it may contain a secret, you will see the following warning message: "Skip output `{output.Key}` since it may contain secret." For more information on how to handle secrets, please refer to the Example: Masking and passing a secret between jobs or workflows.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] To use job outputs in a dependent job, you can use the `needs` context.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Matrices can be used to generate multiple outputs of different names.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] When using a matrix, job outputs will be combined from all jobs inside the matrix.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Actions does not guarantee the order that matrix jobs will run in.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Ensure that the output name is unique, otherwise the last matrix job that runs will override the output value.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] A `map` of variables that are available to all steps in the job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can set variables for the entire workflow or an individual step.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information, see `env` and `jobs.<job_id>.steps[*].env`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Use `jobs.<job_id>.defaults` to create a `map` of default settings that will apply to all steps in the job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can also set default settings for the entire workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Use `jobs.<job_id>.defaults.run` to provide default `shell` and `working-directory` to all `run` steps in the job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can provide default `shell` and `working-directory` options for all `run` steps in a job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can also set default settings for `run` for the entire workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] For more information, see `defaults.run`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] These can be overridden at the `jobs.<job_id>.defaults.run` and `jobs.<job_id>.steps[*].run` levels.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] A job contains a sequence of tasks called `steps`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Steps can run commands, run setup tasks, or run an action in your repository, a public repository, or an action published in a Docker registry.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Not all steps run actions, but all actions run as a step.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Each step runs in its own process in the runner environment and has access to the workspace and filesystem.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] Because steps run in their own process, changes to environment variables are not preserved between steps.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] GitHub provides built-in steps to set up and complete a job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] GitHub only displays the first 1,000 checks, however, you can run an unlimited number of steps as long as you are within the workflow usage limits.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p02] You can use the `id` to reference the step in contexts.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can use the `if` conditional to prevent a step from running unless a condition is met.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] This step only runs when the event type is a `pull_request` and the event action is `unassigned`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The `my backup step` only runs when the previous step of a job fails.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Secrets cannot be directly referenced in `if:` conditionals.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Instead, consider setting secrets as job-level environment variables, then referencing the environment variables to conditionally run steps in the job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If a secret has not been set, the return value of an expression referencing the secret (such as `${{ secrets.SuperSecret }}` in the example) will be an empty string.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information, see Contexts reference and Using secrets in GitHub Actions.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A name for your step to display on GitHub.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Selects an action to run as part of a step in your job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can use an action defined in the same repository as the workflow, a public repository, or in a published Docker container image.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] We strongly recommend that you include the version of the action you are using by specifying a Git ref, SHA, or Docker tag.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If you don't specify a version, it could break your workflows or cause unexpected behavior when the action owner publishes an update.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Some actions require inputs that you must set using the `with` keyword.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Review the action's README file to determine the inputs required.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Actions are either JavaScript files or Docker containers.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If the action you're using is a Docker container you must run the job in a Linux environment.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can specify a branch, ref, or SHA in a public GitHub repository.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A subdirectory in a public GitHub repository at a specific branch, ref, or SHA.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The path to the directory that contains the action in your workflow's repository.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You must check out your repository before using the action.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The path is relative (`./`) to the default working directory (`github.workspace`, `$GITHUB_WORKSPACE`).
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If the action checks out the repository to a location different than the workflow, the relative path used for local actions must be updated.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A public Docker image in the GitHub Packages Container registry.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] This example uses the Google Container Registry at `gcr.io`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If the action is in an internal repository, or in a private repository configured to allow access from your workflow's repository, you can reference the action directly.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information, see Managing GitHub Actions settings for a repository and Managing GitHub Actions settings for a repository.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If the action isn't in a repository configured to allow access, you need to check out the repository and reference the action locally.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Generate a personal access token and add the token as a secret.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The following example shows this method for referencing an action.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information, see Managing your personal access tokens and Using secrets in GitHub Actions.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Replace `PERSONAL_ACCESS_TOKEN` in the example with the name of your secret.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Alternatively, use a GitHub App instead of a personal access token in order to ensure your workflow continues to run even if the personal access token owner leaves.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information, see Making authenticated API requests with a GitHub App in a GitHub Actions workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Runs command-line programs that do not exceed 21,000 characters using the operating system's shell.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If you do not provide a `name`, the step name will default to the text specified in the `run` command.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Commands run using non-login shells by default.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can choose a different shell and customize the shell used to run commands.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information, see `jobs.<job_id>.steps[*].shell`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Each `run` keyword represents a new process and shell in the runner environment.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] When you provide multi-line commands, each line runs in the same shell.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Using the `working-directory` keyword, you can specify the working directory of where to run the command.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Alternatively, you can specify a default working directory for all `run` steps in a job, or for all `run` steps in the entire workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information, see `defaults.run.working-directory` and `jobs.<job_id>.defaults.run.working-directory`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can also use a `run` step to run a script.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information, see Adding scripts to your workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can override the default shell settings in the runner's operating system and the job's default using the `shell` keyword.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can use built-in `shell` keywords, or you can define a custom set of shell options.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The shell command that is run internally executes a temporary file that contains the commands specified in the `run` keyword.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Alternatively, you can specify a default shell for all `run` steps in a job, or for all `run` steps in the entire workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information, see `defaults.run.shell` and `jobs.<job_id>.defaults.run.shell`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can set the `shell` value to a template string using `command [options] {0} [more_options]`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] GitHub interprets the first whitespace-delimited word of the string as the command, and inserts the file name for the temporary script at `{0}`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The command used, `perl` in this example, must be installed on the runner.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For information about the software included on GitHub-hosted runners, see GitHub-hosted runners.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For built-in shell keywords, we provide the following defaults that are executed by GitHub-hosted runners.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You should use these guidelines when running shell scripts.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A `map` of the input parameters defined by the action.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Each input parameter is a key/value pair.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Input parameters are set as environment variables.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The variable is prefixed with `INPUT_` and converted to upper case.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Input parameters defined for a Docker container must use `args`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information, see `jobs.<job_id>.steps[*].with.args`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Defines the three input parameters (`first_name`, `middle_name`, and `last_name`) defined by the `hello_world` action.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] These input variables will be accessible to the `hello-world` action as `INPUT_FIRST_NAME`, `INPUT_MIDDLE_NAME`, and `INPUT_LAST_NAME` environment variables.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A `string` that defines the inputs for a Docker container.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] GitHub passes the `args` to the container's `ENTRYPOINT` when the container starts up.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] An `array of strings` is not supported by this parameter.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A single argument that includes spaces should be surrounded by double quotes `""`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The `args` are used in place of the `CMD` instruction in a `Dockerfile`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use defaults that allow using the action without specifying any `args`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If the action exposes a `--help` flag, or something similar, use that as the default to make your action self-documenting.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Overrides the Docker `ENTRYPOINT` in the `Dockerfile`, or sets it if one wasn't already specified.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Unlike the Docker `ENTRYPOINT` instruction which has a shell and exec form, `entrypoint` keyword accepts only a single string defining the executable to be run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The `entrypoint` keyword is meant to be used with Docker container actions, but you can also use it with JavaScript actions that don't define any inputs.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Sets variables for steps to use in the runner environment.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can also set variables for the entire workflow or a job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information, see `env` and `jobs.<job_id>.env`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Public actions may specify expected variables in the README file.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If you are setting a secret or sensitive value, such as a password or token, you must set secrets using the `secrets` context.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Prevents a job from failing when a step fails.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Set to `true` to allow a job to pass when this step fails.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The maximum number of minutes to run the step before killing the process.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Maximum: 360 for both GitHub-hosted and self-hosted runners.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] `timeout-minutes` must be a positive integer.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Runs a step asynchronously so the job continues to the next step without waiting for it to finish.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use `background: true` for long-running processes, such as databases, servers, or monitoring tasks, that need to run alongside other steps.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You synchronize with background steps later using `wait` or `wait-all` or stop them with `cancel`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can use `background` on steps that use `run` or `uses`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] To reference a background step from `wait` or `cancel`, give it an `id`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A maximum of 10 background steps can run concurrently in a single job; additional background steps are queued until a slot is free.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Outputs and environment changes from a background step are only available after you run a `wait` or `wait-all` step that includes it.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If a background step fails, the job fails at the next `wait` or `wait-all` that includes it (unless `continue-on-error` is set on that step).
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] An implicit `wait-all` runs before any post-job cleanup.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use `background` when you need fine-grained control: starting a long-running process (like a server or database) that stays up while later steps run, referencing a specific step with `wait` or `cancel`, or interleaving background work with other steps.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If you instead have a self-contained group of steps that should all finish before the job continues, `parallel` is a more convenient shorthand.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You cannot use `background` on steps inside a composite action.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A composite action can itself run as a background step, but it cannot declare background steps internally.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Pauses the job until one or more background steps complete.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A `wait` step performs no work itself, it only blocks until the referenced background steps finish.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Provide a single step `id` as a string, or multiple step `id`s as an array.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] After a `wait` step completes, the outputs of the referenced background steps become available to subsequent steps.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If a referenced background step failed, the `wait` step fails too.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A `wait` step always runs and does not support the `if` conditional.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Pauses the job until all active background steps complete.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] This is useful when several background steps are running and you want them all to finish before continuing.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Like `wait`, the `wait-all` step fails if any of the background steps it waits on failed, unless you set `continue-on-error` to `true`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The `wait-all` keyword takes no arguments.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A `wait-all` step always runs and does not support the `if` conditional.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Gracefully terminates a running background step.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The runner sends the step's process a termination signal (`SIGTERM`) so it can clean up, and forcibly stops it (`SIGKILL`) if it does not exit within a short grace period.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The `cancel` keyword targets a single background step by its `id`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A `cancel` step always runs and does not support the `if` conditional.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Runs a group of steps concurrently, then waits for all of them to finish before continuing.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The `parallel` keyword is shorthand: every step in the group runs as a background step, with an implicit `wait` at the end of the group.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use it when you have an independent group of steps that can run at the same time and you don't need to reference them individually.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use `parallel` when you have a self-contained group of steps that should all finish before the job moves on, such as building several components at once.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use `background` when you need finer control: starting a long-running process (like a server or database) that stays up while later steps run, referencing a specific step with `wait` or `cancel`, or interleaving background work with other steps.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] In short, `parallel` is more limited but more convenient for the "run this group at once" case, while `background` is the general-purpose primitive.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Each step in the group is subject to the same 10-step concurrency limit as other background steps.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You cannot use `parallel` inside a composite action.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The group above is equivalent to declaring each step with `background: true` followed by a `wait` step.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The maximum number of minutes to let a job run before GitHub automatically cancels it.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If the timeout exceeds the job execution time limit for the runner, the job will be canceled when the execution time limit is met instead.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information about job execution time limits, see Billing and usage for GitHub-hosted runners and Actions limits for self-hosted runner usage limits.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The `GITHUB_TOKEN` expires when a job finishes or after a maximum of 24 hours.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For self-hosted runners, the token may be the limiting factor if the job timeout is greater than 24 hours.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information on the `GITHUB_TOKEN`, see Use GITHUB_TOKEN for authentication in workflows.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use `jobs.<job_id>.strategy` to use a matrix strategy for your jobs.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A matrix strategy lets you use variables in a single job definition to automatically create multiple job runs that are based on the combinations of the variables.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For example, you can use a matrix strategy to test your code in multiple versions of a language or on multiple operating systems.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information, see Running variations of jobs in a workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use `jobs.<job_id>.strategy.matrix` to define a matrix of different job configurations.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A matrix will generate a maximum of 256 jobs per workflow run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] This limit applies to both GitHub-hosted and self-hosted runners.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The variables that you define become properties in the `matrix` context, and you can reference the property in other areas of your workflow file.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] In this example, you can use `matrix.version` and `matrix.os` to access the current value of `version` and `os` that the job is using.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] By default, GitHub will maximize the number of jobs run in parallel depending on runner availability.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The order of the variables in the matrix determines the order in which the jobs are created.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The first variable you define will be the first job that is created in your workflow run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The following workflow defines the variable `version` with the values `[10, 12, 14]`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The workflow will run three jobs, one for each value in the variable.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Each job will access the `version` value through the `matrix.version` context and pass the value as `node-version` to the `actions/setup-node` action.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Specify multiple variables to create a multi-dimensional matrix.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A job will run for each possible combination of the variables.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The workflow will run six jobs, one for each combination of the `os` and `version` variables.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Each job will set the `runs-on` value to the current `os` value and will pass the current `version` value to the `actions/setup-node` action.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A variable configuration in a matrix can be an `array` of `object`s.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For example, the following matrix produces 4 jobs with corresponding contexts.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Each job in the matrix will have its own combination of `os` and `node` values, as shown below.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For each object in the `include` list, the key:value pairs in the object will be added to each of the matrix combinations if none of the key:value pairs overwrite any of the original matrix values.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If the object cannot be added to any of the matrix combinations, a new matrix combination will be created instead.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Note that the original matrix values will not be overwritten, but added matrix values can be overwritten.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For example, the following workflow will run four jobs, one for each combination of `os` and `node`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] When the job for the `os` value of `windows-latest` and `node` value of `16` runs, an additional variable called `npm` with the value of `6` will be included in the job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For example, this matrix will run 10 jobs, one for each combination of `os` and `version` in the matrix, plus a job for the `os` value of `windows-latest` and `version` value of `17`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If you don't specify any matrix variables, all configurations under `include` will run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For example, the following workflow would run two jobs, one for each `include` entry.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] This lets you take advantage of the matrix strategy without having a fully populated matrix.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] An excluded configuration only has to be a partial match for it to be excluded.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] All `include` combinations are processed after `exclude`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] This allows you to use `include` to add back combinations that were previously excluded.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can control how job failures are handled with `jobs.<job_id>.strategy.fail-fast` and `jobs.<job_id>.continue-on-error`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] `jobs.<job_id>.strategy.fail-fast` applies to the entire matrix.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If `jobs.<job_id>.strategy.fail-fast` is set to `true` or its expression evaluates to `true`, GitHub will cancel all in-progress and queued jobs in the matrix if any job in the matrix fails.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] `jobs.<job_id>.continue-on-error` applies to a single job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If `jobs.<job_id>.continue-on-error` is `true`, other jobs in the matrix will continue running even if the job with `jobs.<job_id>.continue-on-error: true` fails.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can use `jobs.<job_id>.strategy.fail-fast` and `jobs.<job_id>.continue-on-error` together.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For example, the following workflow will start four jobs.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For each job, `continue-on-error` is determined by the value of `matrix.experimental`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If any of the jobs with `continue-on-error: false` fail, all jobs that are in progress or queued will be cancelled.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If the job with `continue-on-error: true` fails, the other jobs will not be affected.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Prevents a workflow run from failing when a job fails.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Set to `true` to allow a workflow run to pass when this job fails.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can allow specific jobs in a job matrix to fail without failing the workflow run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For example, if you wanted to only allow an experimental job with `node` set to `15` to fail without failing the workflow run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use `jobs.<job_id>.container` to create a container to run any steps in a job that don't already specify a container.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If you have steps that use both script and container actions, the container actions will run as sibling containers on the same network with the same volume mounts.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If you do not set a `container`, all steps will run directly on the host specified by `runs-on` unless a step refers to an action configured to run in a container.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The default shell for `run` steps inside a container is `sh` instead of `bash`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] This can be overridden with `jobs.<job_id>.defaults.run` or `jobs.<job_id>.steps[*].shell`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] When you only specify a container image, you can omit the `image` keyword.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use `jobs.<job_id>.container.image` to define the Docker image to use as the container to run the action.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The value can be the Docker Hub image name or a registry name.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Docker Hub normally imposes rate limits on both push and pull operations which will affect jobs on self-hosted runners.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] However, GitHub-hosted runners are not subject to these limits based on an agreement between GitHub and Docker.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If the image's container registry requires authentication to pull the image, you can use `jobs.<job_id>.container.credentials` to set a `map` of the `username` and `password`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The credentials are the same values that you would provide to the `docker login` command.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use `jobs.<job_id>.container.env` to set a `map` of environment variables in the container.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use `jobs.<job_id>.container.ports` to set an `array` of ports to expose on the container.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use `jobs.<job_id>.container.volumes` to set an `array` of volumes for the container to use.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can use volumes to share data between services or other steps in a job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can specify named Docker volumes, anonymous Docker volumes, or bind mounts on the host.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The `<source>` is a volume name or an absolute path on the host machine, and `<destinationPath>` is an absolute path in the container.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use `jobs.<job_id>.container.options` to configure additional Docker container resource options.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For a list of options, see `docker create` options.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The `--network` and `--entrypoint` options are not supported.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Used to host service containers for a job in a workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Service containers are useful for creating databases or cache services like Redis.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The runner automatically creates a Docker network and manages the life cycle of the service containers.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If you configure your job to run in a container, or your step uses container actions, you don't need to map ports to access the service or action.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Docker automatically exposes all ports between containers on the same Docker user-defined bridge network.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can directly reference the service container by its hostname.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The hostname is automatically mapped to the label name you configure for the service in the workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If you configure the job to run directly on the runner machine and your step doesn't use a container action, you must map any required Docker service container ports to the Docker host (the runner machine).
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can access the service container using localhost and the mapped port.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information about the differences between networking service containers, see Communicating with Docker service containers.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] This example creates two services: nginx and redis.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] When you specify the container port but not the host port, the container port is randomly assigned to a free port on the host.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] GitHub sets the assigned host port in the `${{job.services.<service_name>.ports}}` context.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] In this example, you can access the service host ports using the `${{ job.services.nginx.ports['80'] }}` and `${{ job.services.redis.ports['6379'] }}` contexts.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The Docker image to use as the service container to run the action.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If `jobs.<job_id>.services.<service_id>.image` is assigned an empty string, the service will not start.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can use this to set up conditional services, similar to the following example.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Sets a `map` of environment variables in the service container.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Sets an `array` of ports to expose on the service container.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Sets an `array` of volumes for the service container to use.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Additional Docker container resource options.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The `--network` option is not supported.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Overrides the Docker image's default command (`CMD`).
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The value is passed as arguments after the image name in the `docker create` command.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If you also specify `entrypoint`, `command` provides the arguments to that entrypoint.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Overrides the Docker image's default `ENTRYPOINT`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The value is a single string defining the executable to run.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use this when you need to replace the image's entrypoint entirely.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] You can combine `entrypoint` with `command` to pass arguments to the custom entrypoint.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The location and version of a reusable workflow file to run as a job.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] In the first option, `{ref}` can be a SHA, a release tag, or a branch name.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If a release tag and a branch have the same name, the release tag takes precedence over the branch name.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Using the commit SHA is the safest option for stability and security.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] For more information, see Secure use reference.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] If you use the second syntax option (without `{owner}/{repo}` and `@{ref}`) the called workflow is from the same commit as the caller workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Ref prefixes such as `refs/heads` and `refs/tags` are not allowed.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] When a job is used to call a reusable workflow, you can use `with` to provide a map of inputs that are passed to the called workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Any inputs that you pass must match the input specifications defined in the called workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Unlike `jobs.<job_id>.steps[*].with`, the inputs you pass with `jobs.<job_id>.with` are not available as environment variables in the called workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Instead, you can reference the inputs by using the `inputs` context.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A pair consisting of a string identifier for the input and the value of the input.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The identifier must match the name of an input defined by `on.workflow_call.inputs.<inputs_id>` in the called workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The data type of the value must match the type defined by `on.workflow_call.inputs.<input_id>.type` in the called workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Allowed expression contexts: `github`, and `needs`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] When a job is used to call a reusable workflow, you can use `secrets` to provide a map of secrets that are passed to the called workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Any secrets that you pass must match the names defined in the called workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Use the `inherit` keyword to pass all the calling workflow's secrets to the called workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] This includes all secrets the calling workflow has access to, namely organization, repository, and environment secrets.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The `inherit` keyword can be used to pass secrets across repositories within the same organization, or across organizations within the same enterprise.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] A pair consisting of a string identifier for the secret and the value of the secret.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] The identifier must match the name of a secret defined by `on.workflow_call.secrets.<secret_id>` in the called workflow.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p03] Allowed expression contexts: `github`, `needs`, and `secrets`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p04] You can use special characters in path, branch, and tag filters.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p04] The characters `*`, `[`, and `!` are special characters in YAML.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p04] If you start a pattern with `*`, `[`, or `!`, you must enclose the pattern in quotes.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p04] Also, if you use a flow sequence with a pattern containing `[` and/or `]`, the pattern must be enclosed in quotes.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p04] For more information about branch, tag, and path filter syntax, see `on.<push>.<branches|tags>`, `on.<pull_request>.<branches|tags>`, and `on.<push|pull_request>.paths`.
[src:github-actions/workflow-syntax-p04] Path patterns must match the whole path, and start from the repository's root.
